content.text:
Based on my search results, I found several excellent JavaScript unminifier tools on GitHub. Here is a summary of the best options:

## Top JavaScript Unminifier Tools

### 1. **Wakaru** by pionxzh
- **Repository**: https://github.com/pionxzh/wakaru
- **License**: MIT
- **Key Features**:
  - Modern JavaScript/TypeScript unminifier with a playground interface
  - Supports transformation rules for prettifying code
  - Handles module analysis and module mapping
  - Active development with a well-structured monorepo (CLI and playground packages)
  - Uses configurable transformation rule IDs for different prettification levels

### 2. **Webcrack** by j4k0xb
- **Repository**: https://github.com/j4k0xb/webcrack
- **License**: MIT
- **Key Features**:
  - Comprehensive deobfuscation and unminification tool
  - Supports JSX transformation
  - Can unpack bundled code (webpack bundles)
  - Has dedicated deobfuscation capabilities
  - Optional name mangling support
  - Available as both CLI and programmatic API
  - Clean, well-tested codebase

### 3. **Humanify** by jehna
- **Repository**: https://github.com/jehna/humanify
- **License**: MIT
- **Key Features**:
  - AI-powered unminification using LLMs (OpenAI, Gemini, or local models)
  - Intelligently renames minified variable names to human-readable ones
  - Plugin-based architecture (babel, prettier integration)
  - Supports multiple AI providers with configurable context window sizes
  - Uses webcrack as a preprocessing step
  - Unique approach: uses AI to understand code semantics for better naming

### 4. **js-deobfuscator** by kuizuo
- **Repository**: https://github.com/kuizuo/js-deobfuscator
- **License**: MIT
- **Key Features**:
  - Focused on deobfuscation with unminification capabilities
  - Uses Babel AST transformations
  - Handles block statements, sequences, variable declarations
  - Supports JSX parsing
  - Clean separation between deobfuscation and unminification transforms

### 5. **Unminify** by shapesecurity
- **Repository**: https://github.com/shapesecurity/unminify
- **License**: Apache-2.0
- **Key Features**:
  - Configurable safety levels for transformations
  - Supports safe, unsafe, and "wildly unsafe" transforms
  - Includes partial evaluation and inlining capabilities
  - Can add additional custom transforms
  - Works with both source strings and AST trees

### 6. **js-beautify** by beautifier
- **Repository**: https://github.com/beautifier/js-beautify
- **License**: MIT
- **Key Features**:
  - Industry-standard code beautifier/formatter
  - Supports JavaScript, CSS, and HTML
  - Includes unpackers for various obfuscation methods (P.A.C.K.E.R., URL encoding, JavaScriptObfuscator)
  - Widely used and well-maintained
  - Primarily focuses on formatting rather than semantic unminification

### 7. **de4js** by lelinhtinh
- **Repository**: https://github.com/lelinhtinh/de4js
- **License**: MIT
- **Key Features**:
  - Web-based JavaScript deobfuscator
  - Supports multiple encoding/obfuscation formats (jjencode, urlencode, P.A.C.K.E.R., etc.)
  - Uses js-beautify unpackers under the hood
  - Good for quick online deobfuscation tasks

---

## Recommendations by Use Case

| Use Case | Recommended Tool |
|----------|------------------|
| General unminification with modern JS | **Wakaru** or **Webcrack** |
| Webpack bundle unpacking | **Webcrack** |
| AI-powered semantic renaming | **Humanify** |
| Simple code formatting | **js-beautify** |
| Security research / aggressive transforms | **shapesecurity/unminify** |
| Quick online deobfuscation | **de4js** |

The most actively maintained and feature-rich options are **Wakaru**, **Webcrack**, and **Humanify**. For production use, I would recommend starting with **Webcrack** for general unminification tasks, and considering **Humanify** if you need AI-assisted variable renaming for heavily minified code.

Based on my comprehensive search, here is a summary of the best JavaScript deobfuscator tools found on GitHub:

---

## Top JavaScript Deobfuscator Tools

### 1. **webcrack** (j4k0xb/webcrack)
- **Repository**: https://github.com/j4k0xb/webcrack
- **License**: MIT
- **Description**: Deobfuscate, unminify and unpack bundled JavaScript

**Key Features**:
- Handles obfuscator.io obfuscated code
- Unpacks bundled JavaScript (webpack, browserify, etc.)
- AST-based deobfuscation with multiple transformation passes
- Supports string array decoding, control flow recovery, dead code removal
- Uses isolated-vm for safe sandbox execution of decoder functions
- Has both CLI and programmatic API
- Includes a web playground at https://webcrack.netlify.app
- Actively maintained with comprehensive documentation

---

### 2. **REstringer** (HumanSecurity/restringer)
- **Repository**: https://github.com/HumanSecurity/restringer
- **License**: MIT
- **Description**: A JavaScript deobfuscator by Human Security (formerly PerimeterX)

**Key Features**:
- Iterative deobfuscation with configurable max iterations
- Handles nested eval chains (e.g., `eval('eval("eval(3)")')`)
- Modular architecture with separate transformation modules
- CLI tool with verbose/quiet modes
- Can remove dead nodes after deobfuscation
- Built by a security company specializing in bot detection

---

### 3. **obfuscator-io-deobfuscator** (ben-sb/obfuscator-io-deobfuscator)
- **Repository**: https://github.com/ben-sb/obfuscator-io-deobfuscator
- **License**: Apache-2.0
- **Description**: Specifically targets javascript-obfuscator (obfuscator.io) obfuscated code

**Key Features**:
- Babel-based AST transformations
- Constant propagation
- Expression simplification
- Control flow recovery
- Object packing/unpacking
- Anti-tamper removal
- Unused variable removal

---

### 4. **synchrony** (relative/synchrony)
- **Repository**: https://github.com/relative/synchrony
- **License**: GPL-3.0
- **Description**: JavaScript deobfuscator with configurable options

**Key Features**:
- Written in TypeScript
- Supports ECMAScript latest
- Chain expression transformation
- Custom transformer support
- Variable renaming capabilities
- Configurable parsing options (module/script/both)

---

### 5. **js-x-ray** (NodeSecure/js-x-ray)
- **Repository**: https://github.com/NodeSecure/js-x-ray
- **License**: MIT
- **Description**: JavaScript AST analysis focused on security detection

**Key Features**:
- Detects obfuscation patterns rather than just deobfuscating
- Identifies dictionary strings, prefixed identifiers
- Tracks deep binary expressions and encoded array values
- Part of the NodeSecure ecosystem
- Useful for security scanning and malware detection

---

### 6. **JStillery** (mindedsecurity/JStillery)
- **Repository**: https://github.com/mindedsecurity/JStillery
- **License**: GPL-3.0
- **Description**: JavaScript deobfuscator with web interface

**Key Features**:
- jQuery-based web interface
- Browser-based deobfuscation
- Falls back to local processing if server unavailable
- Beautification capabilities

---

### 7. **illuminatejs** (geeksonsecurity/illuminatejs)
- **Repository**: https://github.com/geeksonsecurity/illuminatejs
- **License**: Apache-2.0
- **Description**: JavaScript deobfuscator with playground

**Key Features**:
- React-based playground interface
- Flow-typed codebase
- Interactive input/output comparison

---

### 8. **humanify** (jehna/humanify)
- **Repository**: https://github.com/jehna/humanify
- **License**: MIT
- **Description**: Unminifier that uses webcrack as a plugin

**Key Features**:
- Integrates webcrack for deobfuscation
- Plugin architecture for additional transformations
- Focused on making minified code human-readable

---

## Recommendations

| Use Case | Recommended Tool |
|----------|------------------|
| General deobfuscation + bundle unpacking | **webcrack** |
| obfuscator.io specific code | **obfuscator-io-deobfuscator** or **webcrack** |
| Security analysis/detection | **js-x-ray** |
| Iterative/complex obfuscation | **REstringer** |
| Custom transformer needs | **synchrony** |

The most actively maintained and feature-complete option is **webcrack**, which handles the widest variety of obfuscation techniques and also unpacks bundled code from webpack/browserify.

Based on my research across GitHub repositories, here is a comprehensive summary of the best CSS unminifier and beautifier tools:

---

## Best CSS Unminifier/Beautifier Tools

### 1. **js-beautify (beautifier/js-beautify)**
**Repository:** https://github.com/beautifier/js-beautify

**Key Features:**
- The most widely used CSS beautifier in the ecosystem
- Provides `css_beautify()` function with extensive options
- Used by Microsoft's VS Code CSS Language Service
- Configurable options include:
  - `indent_size` (default: 4) - indentation size
  - `indent_char` (default: space) - character for indentation
  - `selector_separator_newline` (true) - separate selectors with newlines
  - `newline_between_rules` (true) - add newlines after CSS rules
  - `space_around_selector_separator` (false) - spacing around `>`, `+`, `~`
  - `end_with_newline` - whether to end with newline

**Usage:**
```javascript
const { css_beautify } = require('js-beautify');
css_beautify(css_source_text, {
  'indent_size': 2,
  'indent_char': ' '
});
```

---

### 2. **cssbeautify (senchalabs/cssbeautify)**
**Repository:** https://github.com/senchalabs/cssbeautify

**Key Features:**
- Lightweight and focused specifically on CSS
- Simple API with minimal configuration
- Apache-2.0 license
- Options:
  - `indent` - string for indentation (default: 4 spaces)
  - `openbrace` - placement: `'end-of-line'` or `'separate-line'`
  - `autosemicolon` - automatically add missing semicolons

**Usage:**
```javascript
import cssbeautify from 'cssbeautify';
cssbeautify(cssCode, {
  indent: '  ',
  openbrace: 'end-of-line',
  autosemicolon: true
});
```

**Adopted by:** Tencent TDesign, Fela, Twind, cssstats, and many WeChat mini-app decompilers

---

### 3. **Prettier**
**Repository:** https://github.com/prettier/prettier

**Key Features:**
- Opinionated code formatter supporting CSS, SCSS, Less
- Consistent formatting across entire codebases
- Integrates with most editors and CI pipelines
- Uses `parser: 'css'` for CSS files

**Usage:**
```javascript
import * as prettier from 'prettier';
prettier.format(cssCode, { parser: 'css' });
```

---

### 4. **postcss-prettify**
**Repository:** Available on npm as `postcss-prettify`

**Key Features:**
- PostCSS plugin for beautifying CSS output
- Integrates into PostCSS build pipelines
- Used by projects like Tabulator, Ariakit, Vitamin Web (Decathlon)

**Usage:**
```javascript
const postcss = require('postcss');
const prettify = require('postcss-prettify');

postcss([prettify]).process(css);
```

---

### 5. **gulp-cssbeautify**
**Repository:** npm package wrapping cssbeautify for Gulp

**Key Features:**
- Gulp plugin for CSS beautification in build pipelines
- Used by Microsoft Office UI Fabric, Themesberg themes, Creative Tim

**Usage:**
```javascript
const cssbeautify = require('gulp-cssbeautify');
gulp.src('*.css')
  .pipe(cssbeautify())
  .pipe(gulp.dest('dist'));
```

---

### 6. **csstree**
**Repository:** https://github.com/csstree/csstree

**Key Features:**
- Full CSS parser and generator
- Used by SVGO and many CSS manipulation tools
- `csstree.generate()` outputs formatted CSS from AST
- More powerful for programmatic CSS manipulation

**Usage:**
```javascript
const csstree = require('css-tree');
const ast = csstree.parse(minifiedCss);
const beautified = csstree.generate(ast);
```

---

## Recommendation Summary

| Tool | Best For | Complexity |
|------|----------|------------|
| **js-beautify** | General purpose, VS Code integration | Medium |
| **cssbeautify** | Lightweight, simple unminification | Low |
| **Prettier** | Opinionated, consistent team formatting | Low |
| **postcss-prettify** | PostCSS build pipelines | Medium |
| **csstree** | Programmatic CSS manipulation | High |

For simple CSS unminification, **cssbeautify** is the most lightweight option. For comprehensive formatting with more control, **js-beautify** is the industry standard used even by Microsoft's VS Code.

content.text:
For reverse engineering websites and understanding their logic, here's my recommended toolkit:

## Essential Downloads

### 1. **webcrack** (Must-Have)
```bash
npm install -g webcrack
```
- Unpacks webpack/browserify bundles into separate modules
- Deobfuscates obfuscator.io protected code
- Reveals the original file structure of bundled apps

**Usage:**
```bash
webcrack bundle.js -o ./output    # Unpacks to separate files
```

### 2. **wakaru** (Bundle Analysis)
```bash
npm install -g @anthropic-ai/wakaru
```
- Excellent at reconstructing module boundaries
- Shows import/export relationships
- Good for understanding app architecture

### 3. **humanify** (When Logic is Still Unclear)
```bash
npm install -g humanify
```
- Uses AI to rename `a`, `b`, `c` variables to meaningful names like `userToken`, `fetchData`
- Makes deobfuscated code actually understandable
- Requires an LLM API key (OpenAI/local model)

### 4. **REstringer** (Heavy Obfuscation)
```bash
npm install -g restringer
```
- Handles deeply nested eval chains
- Good for malware analysis or heavily protected scripts

---

## Recommended Workflow

```
1. Download target JS files (browser DevTools  Sources tab)
          
2. webcrack bundle.js -o ./output    # Unpack bundles
          
3. Examine file structure, find main logic files
          
4. humanify ./output --local          # AI rename variables (optional)
          
5. Read and analyze the code
```

---

## Browser-Based (No Install)

For quick analysis without installing anything:
- **webcrack playground**: https://webcrack.netlify.app
- **de4js**: https://lelinhtinh.github.io/de4js/

---

## Pro Tips for Website RE

1. **Check for source maps first** - Many sites accidentally ship `.map` files. Look for `//# sourceMappingURL=` in JS files
2. **Network tab** - Watch API calls to understand data flow
3. **React/Vue DevTools** - If the site uses frameworks, their devtools reveal component structure
4. **webcrack's unpack** is the killer feature - it turns one 2MB bundle back into hundreds of organized files

Would you like help setting up any of these tools?

# Wakaru - JavaScript Unminifier

## When to Use
- **Unpacking bundled JavaScript** (webpack, browserify, rollup bundles)
- **Reconstructing module structure** from a single bundled file
- **Understanding app architecture** by seeing original file boundaries
- When you have a large bundle and want to split it into readable modules

## Installation
Already installed in this folder. Run from here:
```bash
npx wakaru <input.js> -o ./output
```

## Common Commands

### Unpack a bundle into separate modules
```bash
npx wakaru bundle.js -o ./unpacked
```

### Unminify a single file
```bash
npx wakaru minified.js -o ./readable
```

## Best For
- Webpack bundles
- Browserify bundles
- Large single-file apps that were originally multiple modules
- Seeing import/export relationships

## Repository
https://github.com/pionxzh/wakaru

# Humanify - AI-Powered Variable Renaming

## When to Use
- **After deobfuscation**, when code is readable but variables are meaningless (a, b, c, _0x123)
- When you need to **understand the logic** but variable names like `t`, `e`, `n` make it impossible
- For **deep reverse engineering** where you need to trace data flow
- When webcrack/wakaru output is still hard to understand

## Installation
Already installed in this folder.

## Requirements
Needs an LLM API key (one of these):
- OpenAI API key (`OPENAI_API_KEY`)
- Local LLM (Ollama)
- Other supported providers

## Common Commands

### With OpenAI
```bash
export OPENAI_API_KEY="your-key"
npx humanify input.js -o output.js
```

### With local Ollama
```bash
npx humanify input.js -o output.js --local
```

## Best For
- Making deobfuscated code actually understandable
- Renaming `function a(b,c,d)` to `function fetchUserData(userId, options, callback)`
- Final step after using webcrack/wakaru

## Repository
https://github.com/jehna/humanify

# js-beautify - Code Formatter

## When to Use
- **Quick formatting** of minified JS/CSS/HTML
- When code is minified but **not obfuscated**
- For **readable output** from compressed production files
- As a **first step** before deeper analysis

## Installation
Already installed in this folder.

## Common Commands

### Beautify JavaScript
```bash
npx js-beautify input.min.js -o output.js
```

### Beautify CSS
```bash
npx css-beautify styles.min.css -o styles.css
```

### Beautify HTML
```bash
npx html-beautify page.min.html -o page.html
```

### With custom indentation
```bash
npx js-beautify -s 2 input.js -o output.js  # 2-space indent
```

## Best For
- Simple minification (whitespace removal)
- CSS/HTML files
- Quick first-pass on any minified code
- When you just need proper indentation

## Limitations
- Does NOT rename variables
- Does NOT deobfuscate code
- Does NOT unpack bundles

## Repository
https://github.com/beautifier/js-beautify

# Webcrack - Deobfuscator & Bundle Unpacker (Web Version)

## When to Use
- **Deobfuscating** JavaScript (obfuscator.io, etc.)
- **Unpacking webpack/browserify bundles** into separate files
- **First step** in reverse engineering any website JS
- When code has string encoding, control flow flattening, or dead code

## How to Use (Web Interface)
Since native installation requires specific Node versions, use the web playground:

** https://webcrack.netlify.app**

1. Open the URL above
2. Paste your obfuscated/bundled JavaScript
3. Click "Deobfuscate" or "Unpack"
4. Download the results

## Features
-  Deobfuscates obfuscator.io output
-  Unpacks webpack bundles into modules
-  Unpacks browserify bundles
-  Removes dead code
-  Decodes string arrays
-  Restores control flow

## Alternative: Use with Docker
```bash
docker run -it --rm -v $(pwd):/work node:18 npx webcrack /work/input.js -o /work/output
```

## Workflow
1. **webcrack** (deobfuscate + unpack) 
2. **wakaru** (further unminify) 
3. **humanify** (AI rename variables)

## Repository
https://github.com/j4k0xb/webcrack

# Wakaru - JavaScript Unminifier

## When to Use
- **Unpacking bundled JavaScript** (webpack, browserify, rollup bundles)
- **Reconstructing module structure** from a single bundled file
- **Understanding app architecture** by seeing original file boundaries
- When you have a large bundle and want to split it into readable modules

## Installation
Already installed in this folder. Run from here:
```bash
npx wakaru <input.js> -o ./output
```

## Common Commands

### Unpack a bundle into separate modules
```bash
npx wakaru bundle.js -o ./unpacked
```

### Unminify a single file
```bash
npx wakaru minified.js -o ./readable
```

## Best For
- Webpack bundles
- Browserify bundles
- Large single-file apps that were originally multiple modules
- Seeing import/export relationships

## Repository
https://github.com/pionxzh/wakaru

# Webcrack - Deobfuscator & Bundle Unpacker (Web Version)

## When to Use
- **Deobfuscating** JavaScript (obfuscator.io, etc.)
- **Unpacking webpack/browserify bundles** into separate files
- **First step** in reverse engineering any website JS
- When code has string encoding, control flow flattening, or dead code

## How to Use (Web Interface)
Since native installation requires specific Node versions, use the web playground:

** https://webcrack.netlify.app**

1. Open the URL above
2. Paste your obfuscated/bundled JavaScript
3. Click "Deobfuscate" or "Unpack"
4. Download the results

## Features
-  Deobfuscates obfuscator.io output
-  Unpacks webpack bundles into modules
-  Unpacks browserify bundles
-  Removes dead code
-  Decodes string arrays
-  Restores control flow

## Alternative: Use with Docker
```bash
docker run -it --rm -v $(pwd):/work node:18 npx webcrack /work/input.js -o /work/output
```

## Workflow
1. **webcrack** (deobfuscate + unpack) 
2. **wakaru** (further unminify) 
3. **humanify** (AI rename variables)

## Repository
https://github.com/j4k0xb/webcrack

# Reverse Engineering Toolkit

A collection of JavaScript unminification, deobfuscation, and analysis tools for reverse engineering websites.

## Tools Included

| Folder | Tool | Purpose |
|--------|------|---------|
| `webcrack-online/` | webcrack | Deobfuscate + unpack bundles (web version) |
| `wakaru/` | wakaru | Unpack bundled JS into modules |
| `humanify/` | humanify | AI-powered variable renaming |
| `js-beautify/` | js-beautify | Format minified JS/CSS/HTML |

## Recommended Workflow

```

  1. EXTRACT: Get JS files from browser DevTools (Sources tab)  

                              

  2. DEOBFUSCATE: Use webcrack (https://webcrack.netlify.app)   
     - Handles obfuscator.io, string encoding, control flow     
     - Unpacks webpack/browserify bundles                        

                              

  3. UNMINIFY: Use wakaru for further module reconstruction     
     cd wakaru && npx wakaru ../output.js -o ../clean           

                              

  4. FORMAT: Use js-beautify for final cleanup                   
     cd js-beautify && npx js-beautify ../clean/*.js            

                              

  5. UNDERSTAND: Use humanify to rename variables (optional)    
     cd humanify && npx humanify ../clean/main.js -o readable.js
     (Requires OpenAI API key or local LLM)                     

```

## Quick Commands

### Format any minified file
```bash
cd js-beautify && npx js-beautify /path/to/file.min.js -o /path/to/output.js
```

### Unpack a webpack bundle
```bash
cd wakaru && npx wakaru /path/to/bundle.js -o /path/to/output/
```

### Deobfuscate (via Docker)
```bash
docker run -it --rm -v $(pwd):/work node:18 npx webcrack /work/input.js -o /work/output
```

### AI rename variables
```bash
export OPENAI_API_KEY="your-key"
cd humanify && npx humanify /path/to/file.js -o /path/to/readable.js
```

## Pro Tips

1. **Check for source maps first** - Look for `//# sourceMappingURL=` in JS files
2. **Browser Network tab** - Watch API calls to understand data flow
3. **React/Vue DevTools** - Reveal component structure if frameworks are used
4. **Start with webcrack** - It handles the most common obfuscation patterns

## Online Tools (No Install)

- **webcrack**: https://webcrack.netlify.app
- **de4js**: https://lelinhtinh.github.io/de4js/
- **beautifier.io**: https://beautifier.io/

# Reverse Engineering Toolkit

A collection of JavaScript unminification, deobfuscation, and analysis tools for reverse engineering websites.

## Tools Included

| Folder | Tool | Purpose |
|--------|------|---------|
| `webcrack-online/` | webcrack | Deobfuscate + unpack bundles (web version) |
| `wakaru/` | wakaru | Unpack bundled JS into modules |
| `humanify/` | humanify | AI-powered variable renaming |
| `js-beautify/` | js-beautify | Format minified JS/CSS/HTML |

## Recommended Workflow

```

  1. EXTRACT: Get JS files from browser DevTools (Sources tab)  

                              

  2. DEOBFUSCATE: Use webcrack (https://webcrack.netlify.app)   
     - Handles obfuscator.io, string encoding, control flow     
     - Unpacks webpack/browserify bundles                        

                              

  3. UNMINIFY: Use wakaru for further module reconstruction     
     cd wakaru && npx wakaru ../output.js -o ../clean           

                              

  4. FORMAT: Use js-beautify for final cleanup                   
     cd js-beautify && npx js-beautify ../clean/*.js            

                              

  5. UNDERSTAND: Use humanify to rename variables (optional)    
     cd humanify && npx humanify ../clean/main.js -o readable.js
     (Requires OpenAI API key or local LLM)                     

```

## Quick Commands

### Format any minified file
```bash
cd js-beautify && npx js-beautify /path/to/file.min.js -o /path/to/output.js
```

### Unpack a webpack bundle
```bash
cd wakaru && npx wakaru /path/to/bundle.js -o /path/to/output/
```

### Deobfuscate (via Docker)
```bash
docker run -it --rm -v $(pwd):/work node:18 npx webcrack /work/input.js -o /work/output
```

### AI rename variables
```bash
export OPENAI_API_KEY="your-key"
cd humanify && npx humanify /path/to/file.js -o /path/to/readable.js
```

## Pro Tips

1. **Check for source maps first** - Look for `//# sourceMappingURL=` in JS files
2. **Browser Network tab** - Watch API calls to understand data flow
3. **React/Vue DevTools** - Reveal component structure if frameworks are used
4. **Start with webcrack** - It handles the most common obfuscation patterns

## Online Tools (No Install)

- **webcrack**: https://webcrack.netlify.app
- **de4js**: https://lelinhtinh.github.io/de4js/
- **beautifier.io**: https://beautifier.io/

content.text:
Based on my analysis, here's the reality:

## The Problem

**The facial calculation logic isn't in these captured files.** Here's why:

### What's Actually Happening

1. **MediaPipe runs client-side** - Loaded from CDN (`cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@mediapipe/tasks-vision`)
   - Detects 478 landmarks (front) / 106 landmarks (side)
   - Returns raw `{x, y}` coordinates

2. **Calculations happen server-side** - The `/api/side-landmarks` endpoint receives the image and returns processed data:
   ```json
   {
     "rotationAngle": -0.411,
     "direction": "right",
     "landmarks": [...],
     "bbox": [317, 316, 495, 644]
   }
   ```

3. **The proprietary formulas are on their backend** - Not in the webpack chunks you captured

### What You Actually Have

| Captured | Contains |
|----------|----------|
| JS chunks | Next.js routing, React components, UI logic |
| HAR | API responses showing raw landmark data |
| Not captured | Server-side calculation logic (Vercel serverless) |

## Your Options

### Option 1: Implement Standard Formulas Yourself

Since MediaPipe landmark indices are documented, you can implement standard facial measurements:

```javascript
// Example: FWHR (Facial Width-to-Height Ratio)
const leftCheek = landmarks[234];
const rightCheek = landmarks[454];
const eyebrow = landmarks[10];
const upperLip = landmarks[13];

const width = distance(leftCheek, rightCheek);
const height = distance(eyebrow, upperLip);
const fwhr = width / height;
```

### Option 2: Reverse Engineer the API

Since you have their API endpoint, you could:
1. Send test images with known landmark positions
2. Record the calculations returned
3. Reverse-engineer the formulas from output patterns

### Option 3: Use Academic References

The measurements they use (FWHR, golden ratio, facial thirds) are standard in:
- Anthropometry research papers
- Plastic surgery literature
- The actual formulas are well-documented

Would you like me to:
1. **Write the standard facial measurement formulas** based on MediaPipe's landmark indices?
2. **Help you capture more API responses** to analyze the calculation patterns?

input.content:
# FaceIQ Labs Reverse Engineering Capture Guide

## Pre-Capture Setup

### 1. Browser Extensions to Install
- React Developer Tools (Chrome/Firefox)
- Redux DevTools (if they use Redux)
- JSON Formatter

### 2. Chrome DevTools Setup
1. Open DevTools (Cmd+Option+I)
2. Go to Network tab
3. Check "Preserve log" 
4. Check "Disable cache" 
5. Set throttling to "No throttling"

### 3. Start Recording
- QuickTime: File  New Screen Recording
- Or use OBS for more control

---

## Capture Flow Checklist

### Step 1: Login Flow
- [ ] Clear cookies first (fresh session)
- [ ] Navigate to beta.faceiqlabs.com
- [ ] Screenshot the login page
- [ ] Complete Google OAuth
- [ ] Screenshot dashboard after login

### Step 2: Dashboard Overview
- [ ] Screenshot the main dashboard
- [ ] Note any existing analyses listed
- [ ] Inspect React components (React DevTools  Components tab)
- [ ] Screenshot component tree

### Step 3: Start New Front Face Analysis
- [ ] Click "New Analysis" or equivalent
- [ ] Screenshot upload UI
- [ ] Upload a front-facing photo
- [ ] **PAUSE HERE** - This is critical:

#### Capture Auto-Detection
- [ ] Watch the Network tab for API calls during detection
- [ ] Look for calls to `/api/faces` or similar
- [ ] Screenshot the detected landmarks overlay
- [ ] Note which landmarks are shown (dots on face)

#### Capture Manual Adjustment UI
- [ ] Screenshot the landmark editor
- [ ] Try dragging a landmark point
- [ ] Watch Network tab - does it send updates?
- [ ] Note the UI controls (zoom, pan, reset, etc.)
- [ ] Count how many landmark points are editable
- [ ] Screenshot the confirmation/save button

### Step 4: Side Profile Analysis
- [ ] Navigate to side profile section
- [ ] Screenshot upload UI
- [ ] Upload a side profile photo
- [ ] Watch for `/api/side-landmarks` call in Network tab
- [ ] Screenshot the detected landmarks
- [ ] Note differences from front face (fewer points?)
- [ ] Test manual adjustment on side profile

### Step 5: Calculations & Results
- [ ] Navigate to results/analysis view
- [ ] Screenshot ALL calculation displays
- [ ] Look for terms like:
  - Facial thirds
  - Golden ratio
  - FWHR (Face Width-Height Ratio)
  - Symmetry scores
  - Canthal tilt
  - Jaw angle
  - Nose angle
- [ ] Hover over each metric - capture tooltips
- [ ] Screenshot any charts/visualizations

### Step 6: Premium Features
- [ ] Try to access "Harmony Analysis" or premium features
- [ ] Screenshot the paywall/unlock modal
- [ ] Note what's locked vs free

---

## Technical Capture Details

### Network Tab - Key Requests to Capture

```
POST /api/faces               Creates new analysis, returns face ID
POST /api/side-landmarks      Processes side profile
GET  /api/faces/:id           Retrieves analysis data
POST /api/analysis/unlock     Premium feature unlock
GET  /api/subscription        User's plan/quota
```

For each request, right-click  "Copy as cURL" to save the exact request format.

### React DevTools - What to Look For

1. **Component Names** - Look for:
   - `FaceLandmarker` or `LandmarkEditor`
   - `FaceCanvas` or `LandmarkCanvas`
   - `PointDragger` or `DraggablePoint`
   - `AnalysisResults` or `Measurements`

2. **Props to Note**:
   - `landmarks` array structure
   - `onLandmarkChange` callback pattern
   - `selectedLandmark` state
   - `zoom`, `pan`, `scale` values

3. **State Management**:
   - Look for Context providers
   - Check for Zustand/Redux stores
   - Note how landmark positions are stored

### Console Tab - Useful Commands

```javascript
// Find React fiber (internal React state)
const root = document.getElementById('__next');
const fiber = root._reactRootContainer?._internalRoot?.current;

// Log current state
console.log(fiber);

// Find specific components
const findComponents = (fiber, name, results = []) => {
  if (fiber.type?.name === name) results.push(fiber);
  if (fiber.child) findComponents(fiber.child, name, results);
  if (fiber.sibling) findComponents(fiber.sibling, name, results);
  return results;
};

// Example: Find all Canvas components
findComponents(fiber, 'Canvas');
```

---

## Post-Capture: What to Extract

### From HAR File
```bash
# Extract all API responses
python3 << 'EOF'
import json
with open('faceiq.har', 'r') as f:
    har = json.load(f)

for entry in har['log']['entries']:
    url = entry['request']['url']
    if 'faceiqlabs.com/api/' in url:
        print(f"\n=== {entry['request']['method']} {url} ===")
        if 'response' in entry and 'content' in entry['response']:
            content = entry['response']['content']
            if 'text' in content:
                try:
                    print(json.dumps(json.loads(content['text']), indent=2)[:2000])
                except:
                    print(content['text'][:500])
EOF
```

### From Screen Recording
1. Note exact timing of each step
2. Document all UI states
3. Capture any animations/transitions
4. Note loading states and spinners

### From Screenshots
1. Annotate landmark positions
2. Document color schemes
3. Note typography and spacing
4. Capture all icons/assets

---

## Landmark Mapping

### Front Face - MediaPipe 478 Points
Key landmarks to identify in their UI:

| Feature | Likely MediaPipe Index |
|---------|----------------------|
| Left eye outer | 33 |
| Left eye inner | 133 |
| Right eye inner | 362 |
| Right eye outer | 263 |
| Nose tip | 4 |
| Nose bridge | 6 |
| Upper lip center | 13 |
| Lower lip center | 14 |
| Chin | 152 |
| Left cheekbone | 234 |
| Right cheekbone | 454 |
| Left eyebrow | 70 |
| Right eyebrow | 300 |
| Left jaw | 172 |
| Right jaw | 397 |

### Side Profile - 106 Points
From your HAR, they return 106 landmarks for side view. Key ones:

| Feature | Approximate Index |
|---------|------------------|
| Forehead | 0-10 |
| Nose bridge | 15-25 |
| Nose tip | 30-35 |
| Upper lip | 40-50 |
| Chin | 60-70 |
| Jaw line | 80-100 |

---

## Files to Save

After capture, organize like this:

```
faceiq-capture/
 har/
    full-session.har
 screenshots/
    01-login.png

toolUseResult.content:
# FaceIQ Labs Reverse Engineering Capture Guide

## Pre-Capture Setup

### 1. Browser Extensions to Install
- React Developer Tools (Chrome/Firefox)
- Redux DevTools (if they use Redux)
- JSON Formatter

### 2. Chrome DevTools Setup
1. Open DevTools (Cmd+Option+I)
2. Go to Network tab
3. Check "Preserve log" 
4. Check "Disable cache" 
5. Set throttling to "No throttling"

### 3. Start Recording
- QuickTime: File  New Screen Recording
- Or use OBS for more control

---

## Capture Flow Checklist

### Step 1: Login Flow
- [ ] Clear cookies first (fresh session)
- [ ] Navigate to beta.faceiqlabs.com
- [ ] Screenshot the login page
- [ ] Complete Google OAuth
- [ ] Screenshot dashboard after login

### Step 2: Dashboard Overview
- [ ] Screenshot the main dashboard
- [ ] Note any existing analyses listed
- [ ] Inspect React components (React DevTools  Components tab)
- [ ] Screenshot component tree

### Step 3: Start New Front Face Analysis
- [ ] Click "New Analysis" or equivalent
- [ ] Screenshot upload UI
- [ ] Upload a front-facing photo
- [ ] **PAUSE HERE** - This is critical:

#### Capture Auto-Detection
- [ ] Watch the Network tab for API calls during detection
- [ ] Look for calls to `/api/faces` or similar
- [ ] Screenshot the detected landmarks overlay
- [ ] Note which landmarks are shown (dots on face)

#### Capture Manual Adjustment UI
- [ ] Screenshot the landmark editor
- [ ] Try dragging a landmark point
- [ ] Watch Network tab - does it send updates?
- [ ] Note the UI controls (zoom, pan, reset, etc.)
- [ ] Count how many landmark points are editable
- [ ] Screenshot the confirmation/save button

### Step 4: Side Profile Analysis
- [ ] Navigate to side profile section
- [ ] Screenshot upload UI
- [ ] Upload a side profile photo
- [ ] Watch for `/api/side-landmarks` call in Network tab
- [ ] Screenshot the detected landmarks
- [ ] Note differences from front face (fewer points?)
- [ ] Test manual adjustment on side profile

### Step 5: Calculations & Results
- [ ] Navigate to results/analysis view
- [ ] Screenshot ALL calculation displays
- [ ] Look for terms like:
  - Facial thirds
  - Golden ratio
  - FWHR (Face Width-Height Ratio)
  - Symmetry scores
  - Canthal tilt
  - Jaw angle
  - Nose angle
- [ ] Hover over each metric - capture tooltips
- [ ] Screenshot any charts/visualizations

### Step 6: Premium Features
- [ ] Try to access "Harmony Analysis" or premium features
- [ ] Screenshot the paywall/unlock modal
- [ ] Note what's locked vs free

---

## Technical Capture Details

### Network Tab - Key Requests to Capture

```
POST /api/faces               Creates new analysis, returns face ID
POST /api/side-landmarks      Processes side profile
GET  /api/faces/:id           Retrieves analysis data
POST /api/analysis/unlock     Premium feature unlock
GET  /api/subscription        User's plan/quota
```

For each request, right-click  "Copy as cURL" to save the exact request format.

### React DevTools - What to Look For

1. **Component Names** - Look for:
   - `FaceLandmarker` or `LandmarkEditor`
   - `FaceCanvas` or `LandmarkCanvas`
   - `PointDragger` or `DraggablePoint`
   - `AnalysisResults` or `Measurements`

2. **Props to Note**:
   - `landmarks` array structure
   - `onLandmarkChange` callback pattern
   - `selectedLandmark` state
   - `zoom`, `pan`, `scale` values

3. **State Management**:
   - Look for Context providers
   - Check for Zustand/Redux stores
   - Note how landmark positions are stored

### Console Tab - Useful Commands

```javascript
// Find React fiber (internal React state)
const root = document.getElementById('__next');
const fiber = root._reactRootContainer?._internalRoot?.current;

// Log current state
console.log(fiber);

// Find specific components
const findComponents = (fiber, name, results = []) => {
  if (fiber.type?.name === name) results.push(fiber);
  if (fiber.child) findComponents(fiber.child, name, results);
  if (fiber.sibling) findComponents(fiber.sibling, name, results);
  return results;
};

// Example: Find all Canvas components
findComponents(fiber, 'Canvas');
```

---

## Post-Capture: What to Extract

### From HAR File
```bash
# Extract all API responses
python3 << 'EOF'
import json
with open('faceiq.har', 'r') as f:
    har = json.load(f)

for entry in har['log']['entries']:
    url = entry['request']['url']
    if 'faceiqlabs.com/api/' in url:
        print(f"\n=== {entry['request']['method']} {url} ===")
        if 'response' in entry and 'content' in entry['response']:
            content = entry['response']['content']
            if 'text' in content:
                try:
                    print(json.dumps(json.loads(content['text']), indent=2)[:2000])
                except:
                    print(content['text'][:500])
EOF
```

### From Screen Recording
1. Note exact timing of each step
2. Document all UI states
3. Capture any animations/transitions
4. Note loading states and spinners

### From Screenshots
1. Annotate landmark positions
2. Document color schemes
3. Note typography and spacing
4. Capture all icons/assets

---

## Landmark Mapping

### Front Face - MediaPipe 478 Points
Key landmarks to identify in their UI:

| Feature | Likely MediaPipe Index |
|---------|----------------------|
| Left eye outer | 33 |
| Left eye inner | 133 |
| Right eye inner | 362 |
| Right eye outer | 263 |
| Nose tip | 4 |
| Nose bridge | 6 |
| Upper lip center | 13 |
| Lower lip center | 14 |
| Chin | 152 |
| Left cheekbone | 234 |
| Right cheekbone | 454 |
| Left eyebrow | 70 |
| Right eyebrow | 300 |
| Left jaw | 172 |
| Right jaw | 397 |

### Side Profile - 106 Points
From your HAR, they return 106 landmarks for side view. Key ones:

| Feature | Approximate Index |
|---------|------------------|
| Forehead | 0-10 |
| Nose bridge | 15-25 |
| Nose tip | 30-35 |
| Upper lip | 40-50 |
| Chin | 60-70 |
| Jaw line | 80-100 |

---

## Files to Save

After capture, organize like this:

```
faceiq-capture/
 har/
    full-session.har
 screenshots/
    01-login.png
    02-dashboard.png
    03-upload-front.png
    04-auto-detect.png
    05-manual-adjust.png
    06-upload-side.png
    07-side-detect.png
    08-results.png
    09-premium.png
 recordings/
    full-flow.mp4
 api-responses/
    faces-list.json
    face-create.json
    side-landmarks.json
    subscription.json
 components/
    react-tree.txt
 notes/
     measurements-list.md
     ui-patterns.md
```

#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Extract FaceIQ API responses from HAR file"""

import json
import os

HAR_PATH = os.path.expanduser("~/Desktop/FACEIQ.har")
OUTPUT_DIR = os.path.expanduser("~/Desktop/reverse-engineer/extracted-api")

os.makedirs(OUTPUT_DIR, exist_ok=True)

print(f"Loading HAR file: {HAR_PATH}")
with open(HAR_PATH, 'r') as f:
    har = json.load(f)

print(f"Total entries: {len(har['log']['entries'])}")

# Find all FaceIQ API calls
api_calls = []
for entry in har['log']['entries']:
    url = entry['request']['url']
    if 'beta.faceiqlabs.com/api/' in url:
        api_calls.append(entry)

print(f"Found {len(api_calls)} FaceIQ API calls\n")

# Extract each API call
for i, entry in enumerate(api_calls):
    method = entry['request']['method']
    url = entry['request']['url']

    # Get endpoint name
    endpoint = url.split('beta.faceiqlabs.com')[1].split('?')[0]
    safe_name = endpoint.replace('/', '_').strip('_')

    print(f"=== {method} {endpoint} ===")

    # Get response
    response = entry.get('response', {})
    content = response.get('content', {})

    # Save request info
    output = {
        'method': method,
        'url': url,
        'status': response.get('status'),
        'request_headers': {h['name']: h['value'] for h in entry['request'].get('headers', [])},
        'request_body': None,
        'response_headers': {h['name']: h['value'] for h in response.get('headers', [])},
        'response_body': None
    }

    # Get request body if POST
    if method == 'POST':
        post_data = entry['request'].get('postData', {})
        if 'text' in post_data:

#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Extract FaceIQ API responses from HAR file"""

import json
import os

HAR_PATH = os.path.expanduser("~/Desktop/FACEIQ.har")
OUTPUT_DIR = os.path.expanduser("~/Desktop/reverse-engineer/extracted-api")

os.makedirs(OUTPUT_DIR, exist_ok=True)

print(f"Loading HAR file: {HAR_PATH}")
with open(HAR_PATH, 'r') as f:
    har = json.load(f)

print(f"Total entries: {len(har['log']['entries'])}")

# Find all FaceIQ API calls
api_calls = []
for entry in har['log']['entries']:
    url = entry['request']['url']
    if 'beta.faceiqlabs.com/api/' in url:
        api_calls.append(entry)

print(f"Found {len(api_calls)} FaceIQ API calls\n")

# Extract each API call
for i, entry in enumerate(api_calls):
    method = entry['request']['method']
    url = entry['request']['url']

    # Get endpoint name
    endpoint = url.split('beta.faceiqlabs.com')[1].split('?')[0]
    safe_name = endpoint.replace('/', '_').strip('_')

    print(f"=== {method} {endpoint} ===")

    # Get response
    response = entry.get('response', {})
    content = response.get('content', {})

    # Save request info
    output = {
        'method': method,
        'url': url,
        'status': response.get('status'),
        'request_headers': {h['name']: h['value'] for h in entry['request'].get('headers', [])},
        'request_body': None,
        'response_headers': {h['name']: h['value'] for h in response.get('headers', [])},
        'response_body': None
    }

    # Get request body if POST
    if method == 'POST':
        post_data = entry['request'].get('postData', {})
        if 'text' in post_data:
            try:
                output['request_body'] = json.loads(post_data['text'])
            except:
                output['request_body'] = post_data.get('text', '')[:1000]

    # Get response body
    if 'text' in content:
        try:
            body = json.loads(content['text'])
            output['response_body'] = body

            # Pretty print key data
            if 'data' in body and 'landmarks' in str(body.get('data', {})):
                print(f"   Contains landmark data!")
                if isinstance(body.get('data'), dict):
                    data = body['data']
                    print(f"     rotationAngle: {data.get('rotationAngle')}")
                    print(f"     direction: {data.get('direction')}")
                    print(f"     landmarks count: {len(data.get('landmarks', []))}")
            elif 'faces' in body:
                print(f"   Contains {len(body.get('faces', []))} face(s)")
            elif 'quotaUsage' in body:
                print(f"   Subscription/quota info")
            elif 'error' in body:
                print(f"   Error: {body.get('error')}")
            else:
                print(f"   Response keys: {list(body.keys())}")

        except json.JSONDecodeError:
            output['response_body'] = content.get('text', '')[:500]
            print(f"   Non-JSON response")

    # Save to file
    filename = f"{i:02d}_{method}_{safe_name}.json"
    filepath = os.path.join(OUTPUT_DIR, filename)
    with open(filepath, 'w') as f:
        json.dump(output, f, indent=2)
    print(f"   Saved to {filename}\n")

print(f"\nAll API responses saved to: {OUTPUT_DIR}")

# Create summary
summary_path = os.path.join(OUTPUT_DIR, "00_SUMMARY.md")
with open(summary_path, 'w') as f:
    f.write("# FaceIQ API Endpoints Summary\n\n")

# FaceIQ Data Capture Scripts

## How to Use These Scripts

### Step 1: Open FaceIQ in Chrome
Go to https://beta.faceiqlabs.com and log in

### Step 2: Open DevTools
Press `Cmd + Option + I` (Mac) or `F12` (Windows)

### Step 3: Paste the Capture Script
Go to the **Console** tab and paste the contents of `capture-all.js`

### Step 4: Use the Site Normally
- Upload a front face photo
- Adjust landmarks if needed
- Upload a side profile
- View results

### Step 5: Export Captured Data
In the console, run:
```javascript
FaceIQCapture.export()
```

This will download a JSON file with all captured data.

---

## What Gets Captured

| Data | Source | Description |
|------|--------|-------------|
| MediaPipe landmarks | Client-side | 478 facial points from front face |
| API responses | Network | All /api/* calls and responses |
| React state | DOM | Component state if accessible |
| User adjustments | Events | Any manual landmark adjustments |
| Calculation results | DOM | Scraped from results UI |

---

## Troubleshooting

### "FaceLandmarker is not defined"
The MediaPipe library loads dynamically. Wait until you see the face detection UI, then the intercept will work.

### Script doesn't capture landmarks
Make sure you paste the script BEFORE uploading a photo. The intercept needs to be in place first.

### Data looks incomplete
Run `FaceIQCapture.status()` to see what has been captured so far.

- `getScoreColorRGB()` function for score visualization

#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Extract calculation-related code from FaceIQ minified JavaScript"""

import re
import os

JS_PATH = os.path.expanduser("~/Desktop/FACEIQHAR/dashboard-front/_next/static/chunks/053ca3e7db98a078-q82d43b8cac.js")
OUTPUT_PATH = os.path.expanduser("~/Desktop/reverse-engineer/extracted-calculations.txt")

print(f"Reading: {JS_PATH}")
with open(JS_PATH, 'r') as f:
    js_content = f.read()

print(f"File size: {len(js_content):,} characters")

# Patterns to search for
patterns = {
    "Math operations": r'Math\.(sqrt|atan2|pow|abs|cos|sin|tan|PI|floor|ceil|round)\([^)]+\)',
    "Distance calculations": r'\b(distance|dist)\s*[=:]\s*[^;,]+',
    "Angle calculations": r'\b(angle|tilt|rotation)\s*[=:]\s*[^;,]+',
    "Ratio calculations": r'\b(ratio|fwhr|golden)\s*[=:]\s*[^;,]+',
    "Score functions": r'\b(score|Score|getScore|calculateScore)[^(]*\([^)]*\)',
    "Landmark references": r'landmarks?\[\d+\]',
    "Width/Height": r'\b(width|height)\s*[=:]\s*[^;,]+(?:landmark|point)',
    "Coordinate access": r'\.[xy]\b',
    "Function definitions with calc/score/measure": r'function\s+\w*(calc|score|measure|ratio|angle|distance)\w*\s*\([^)]*\)',
    "Arrow functions with math": r'\([^)]*\)\s*=>\s*\{[^}]*Math\.',
    "Object with idealMin/idealMax": r'\{[^}]*ideal(?:Min|Max)[^}]*\}',
    "Facial features": r'(Trichion|Glabella|Nasion|Pronasale|Subnasale|Pogonion|Menton|Gonion|canthal|nasolabial|gonial)',
}

results = {}
for name, pattern in patterns.items():
    matches = re.findall(pattern, js_content, re.IGNORECASE)
    if matches:
        # Deduplicate and limit
        unique_matches = list(set(matches))[:50]
        results[name] = unique_matches
        print(f"\n{name}: {len(matches)} matches (showing {len(unique_matches)} unique)")
        for m in unique_matches[:10]:
            if isinstance(m, str) and len(m) < 200:
                print(f"  - {m[:100]}")

# Look for longer calculation blocks
print("\n\n=== Searching for calculation blocks ===")

# Find function blocks containing calculation keywords
calc_block_pattern = r'function\s*\w*\s*\([^)]*\)\s*\{[^}]{50,500}(?:Math\.|score|ratio|angle|distance)[^}]{0,500}\}'
calc_blocks = re.findall(calc_block_pattern, js_content, re.IGNORECASE)
print(f"\nFound {len(calc_blocks)} potential calculation function blocks")

# Find objects with measurement configurations
config_pattern = r'\{[^{}]{20,500}(?:idealMin|idealMax|scoreWeight|harmonyScore)[^{}]{0,500}\}'
configs = re.findall(config_pattern, js_content, re.IGNORECASE)
print(f"Found {len(configs)} potential configuration objects")

# Save all findings
with open(OUTPUT_PATH, 'w') as f:
    f.write("# FaceIQ Calculation Code Extraction\n\n")

    for name, matches in results.items():
        f.write(f"\n## {name}\n")
        for m in matches:
            if isinstance(m, str):
                f.write(f"- {m}\n")

    f.write("\n\n## Calculation Function Blocks\n")
    for i, block in enumerate(calc_blocks[:20]):
        f.write(f"\n### Block {i+1}\n```javascript\n{block}\n```\n")

    f.write("\n\n## Configuration Objects\n")
    for i, config in enumerate(configs[:20]):
        f.write(f"\n### Config {i+1}\n```javascript\n{config}\n```\n")

print(f"\nResults saved to: {OUTPUT_PATH}")

# Also search for specific known patterns from the summary
print("\n\n=== Searching for known FaceIQ patterns ===")

known_patterns = [
    r'getScoreColorRGB',
    r'harmonyAnalysis',
    r'facialThirds',
    r'symmetryScore',
    r'goldenRatio',
    r'faceLandmarks',
    r'sideLandmarks',
    r'cephalometric',
]

for pattern in known_patterns:
    matches = re.findall(f'.{{0,50}}{pattern}.{{0,50}}', js_content, re.IGNORECASE)
    if matches:
        print(f"\n{pattern}: {len(matches)} occurrences")
        for m in matches[:3]:
            print(f"  ...{m}...")

    sys.exit(1)

entries = har.get('log', {}).get('entries', [])
print(f"Total entries: {len(entries)}")

# Find all FaceIQ API calls
api_calls = []
for entry in entries:

    if 'faceiqlabs.com/api/' in url:
        api_calls.append(entry)

print(f"Found {len(api_calls)} FaceIQ API calls\n")

# Process each API call
for i, entry in enumerate(api_calls):
    request = entry.get('request', {})
    response = entry.get('response', {})

    method = request.get('method', 'UNKNOWN')
    url = request.get('url', '')
    status = response.get('status', 0)

    print(f"\n{'='*60}")

    print(f"Status: {status}")

    # Get response body
    content = response.get('content', {})
    body_text = content.get('text', '')

    if body_text:

            # Save full response
            safe_name = endpoint.replace('/', '_').strip('_')
            filename = f"{i:02d}_{method}_{safe_name}.json"

            with open(filepath, 'w') as f:
                json.dump({
                    'endpoint': endpoint,

                }, f, indent=2)

            print(f"Saved: {filename}")

            # Check for landmark data

                print("  -> CONTAINS LANDMARKS!")

                # Extract landmark details
                if isinstance(body, dict):
                    if 'data' in body and isinstance(body['data'], dict):
                        data = body['data']
                        landmarks = data.get('landmarks', [])
                        print(f"  -> Landmark count: {len(landmarks)}")
                        if landmarks and len(landmarks) > 0:

            if found_scores:
                print(f"  -> Contains score-related keys!")

        except json.JSONDecodeError:
            print(f"  -> Non-JSON response (length: {len(body_text)})")

# Also check for subscription/features data
print("\n\n" + "="*60)
print("SUBSCRIPTION/FEATURE DATA:")
print("="*60)

for i, entry in enumerate(api_calls):
    url = entry.get('request', {}).get('url', '')
    if 'subscription' in url.lower() or 'unlock' in url.lower() or 'feature' in url.lower():
        content = entry.get('response', {}).get('content', {})

1# FaceIQ Labs - Facial Analysis Calculation Analysis Report

     3**Analysis Date:** 2025-12-18
     4**HAR File:** /Users/imorgado/Desktop/FACEIQ.har (68.13 MB)
     5**JavaScript Files:** /Users/imorgado/Desktop/FACEIQHAR/
     6
     7---
     8
     9## Executive Summary
    10
    11This report documents the findings from reverse-engineering the FaceIQ Labs facial analysis platform. The analysis reveals that:
    12
    131. **Landmark detection is performed server-side** via API calls
    142. **Side profile analysis uses 106 facial landmarks**
    153. **Calculation formulas are NOT present in client-side JavaScript** - all computations happen on the backend
    164. **The frontend is a Next.js React application** with minified production code
    17
    18---
    19
    20## 1. API Endpoints Discovered
    21
    22### 1.1 Core Endpoints
    23
    24| Endpoint | Method | Purpose |
    25|----------|--------|---------|
    26| `/api/auth/session` | GET | User session management |
    27| `/api/auth/callback/google` | GET | Google OAuth callback |
    28| `/api/faces` | GET/POST | Face image management |
    29| `/api/side-landmarks` | POST | **Side profile landmark detection** |
    30| `/api/subscription` | GET | User subscription status |
    31| `/api/analysis/unlock` | POST | Premium feature unlock |
    32| `/api/faces/[id]/surgery-consent` | POST | Surgery simulation consent |
    33
    34### 1.2 Endpoint Details
    35
    36#### /api/side-landmarks (POST)
    37**This is the key endpoint for landmark detection.**
    38
    39**Request:** Image data posted to server
    40**Response Structure:**
    41```json
    42{
    43  "success": true,
    44  "data": {
    45    "rotationAngle": -0.4113050062109639,
    46    "direction": "right",
    47    "center": {"x": 381.039, "y": 479.534},
    48    "crop": {
    49      "x": 154,
    50      "y": 228,
    51      "width": 505,
    52      "height": 505,
    53      "scale": 2.029268292682927
    54    },
    55    "landmarks": [/* 106 coordinate pairs */],
    56    "bbox": [317, 316, 495, 644]
    57  }
    58}
    59```
    60
    61#### /api/subscription (GET)
    62**Response Structure:**
    63```json
    64{
    65  "subscription": null,
    66  "quotaUsage": {
    67    "mappings": {
    68      "used": 1,
    69      "limit": 20,
    70      "remaining": 19,
    71      "resetsAt": "2025-12-18T23:59:59.999Z"
    72    },
    73    "harmonyAnalysis": {
    74      "used": 0,
    75      "limit": 0,
    76      "remaining": 0,
    77      "resetsAt": "1970-01-01T00:00:00.000Z"
    78    },
    79    "dataExports": {
    80      "used": 0,
    81      "limit": 1,
    82      "remaining": 1
    83    }
    84  },
    85  "retentionOfferClaimed": false,
    86  "hasFreeUnlock": false
    87}
    88```
    89
    90---
    91
    92## 2. Side Profile Landmark Data (106 Points)
    93
    94The `/api/side-landmarks` endpoint returns 106 facial landmark coordinates for side profile analysis.
    95
    96### 2.1 Landmark Coordinate Format
    97```json
    98{
    99  "x": 484.7926025390625,
   100  "y": 623.1043701171875
   101}
   102```
   103
   104All coordinates are floating-point values representing pixel positions in the processed image.
   105
   106### 2.2 Landmark Index Mapping (Inferred from Analysis)
   107
   108Based on standard cephalometric analysis and the landmark count (106), the indices likely correspond to:
   109
   110#### Face Contour (Indices 0-16)
   111| Index | Probable Feature |
   112|-------|-----------------|
   113| 0 | Menton (chin bottom) |
   114| 1-8 | Mandible contour |
   115| 9-16 | Cheek/Ear contour |
   116
   117#### Nose Profile (Indices 17-33)
   118| Index | Probable Feature |
   119|-------|-----------------|
   120| 17 | Trichion (hairline reference) |
   121| 18-24 | Forehead/Nasion area |
   122| 25-33 | Nose bridge and tip |
   123
   124#### Eye Region (Indices 34-51)
   125| Index | Probable Feature |
   126|-------|-----------------|
   127| 34-42 | Eye contour points |
   128| 43-51 | Brow and eyelid markers |
   129
   130#### Nose/Lip Region (Indices 52-75)
   131| Index | Probable Feature |
   132|-------|-----------------|
   133| 52-63 | Nasal landmarks |
   134| 64-75 | Upper/lower lip markers |
   135
   136#### Additional Points (Indices 76-105)
   137| Index | Probable Feature |
   138|-------|-----------------|
   139| 76-85 | Brow profile points |
   140| 86-95 | Ear and jaw markers |
   141| 96-105 | Precision adjustment points |
   142
   143### 2.3 Key Anatomical Landmarks Referenced
   144
   145From the landmark image URLs found in HAR:
   146- `hairline.webp` - Trichion
   147- `leftEyePupil.webp` / `rightEyePupil.webp` - Pupil centers
   148- `noseLeft.webp` / `noseRight.webp` - Alar base
   149- `lowerLip.webp` - Vermilion border
   150- `chinBottom.webp` - Menton
   151- `leftOuterEar.webp` / `rightOuterEar.webp` - Tragion
   152- `leftTemple.webp` / `rightTemple.webp` - Temporal points
   153- `leftEyeMedialCanthus.webp` - Inner eye corner
   154- `leftEyeLateralCanthus.webp` - Outer eye corner
   155- `leftEyeUpperEyelid.webp` / `leftEyeLowerEyelid.webp` - Eyelid margins
   156- `leftBrowHead.webp` / `leftBrowArch.webp` / `leftBrowTail.webp` - Brow points
   157- `leftUpperEyelidCrease.webp` - Crease position
   158
   159---
   160
   161## 3. Calculation Formulas (Server-Side)
   162
   163**IMPORTANT:** The actual calculation formulas are NOT present in the client-side JavaScript. All calculations are performed server-side. The following are **standard formulas** used in facial analysis that the system likely implements:
   164
   165### 3.1 FWHR (Facial Width-to-Height Ratio)
   166
   167**Standard Formula:**
   168```
   169FWHR = Bizygomatic Width / Upper Face Height
   170     = (Zygion_L to Zygion_R) / (Nasion to Upper Lip)
   171```
   172
   173**Typical Values:**
   174- Male ideal: 1.8 - 2.1
   175- Female ideal: 1.6 - 1.9
   176
   177### 3.2 Golden Ratio Measurements
   178
   179**Standard Formula:**
   180```
   181Phi (Golden Ratio) = 1.618
   182
   183Measurements tested:
   184- Face length / Face width
   185- Lip to chin / Nose to lip
   186- Nose width / Mouth width
   187- Eye width / Interpupillary distance
   188```
   189
   190### 3.3 Facial Thirds
   191
   192**Standard Formula:**
   193```
   194Upper Third = Trichion to Glabella
   195Middle Third = Glabella to Subnasale
   196Lower Third = Subnasale to Menton
   197
   198Ideal: Each third = 33.3% of total face height
   199```
   200
   201### 3.4 Canthal Tilt
   202
   203**Standard Formula:**
   204```
   205Canthal Tilt = atan2(
   206  (Lateral_Canthus_Y - Medial_Canthus_Y),
   207  (Lateral_Canthus_X - Medial_Canthus_X)
   208) * (180 / PI)
   209
   210Positive value = positive canthal tilt (desirable)
   211Ideal range: +4 to +8 degrees
   212```
   213
   214### 3.5 Nasolabial Angle (Side Profile)
   215
   216**Standard Formula:**
   217```
   218Nasolabial Angle = angle between:
   219  - Line from Columella to Subnasale
   220  - Line from Subnasale to Labrale Superius
   221
   222Ideal range: 90-120 degrees (varies by gender)
   223- Male: 90-95 degrees
   224- Female: 100-110 degrees
   225```
   226
   227### 3.6 Gonial Angle (Side Profile)
   228
   229**Standard Formula:**
   230```
   231Gonial Angle = angle at the Gonion point between:
   232  - Mandibular plane (Gonion to Menton)
   233  - Ramus line (Gonion to Condylion)
   234
   235Ideal range: 120-130 degrees
   236```
   237
   238### 3.7 Distance Calculation (General)
   239
   240**Standard Formula:**
   241```javascript
   242function distance(p1, p2) {
   243  return Math.sqrt(
   244    Math.pow(p2.x - p1.x, 2) +
   245    Math.pow(p2.y - p1.y, 2)
   246  );
   247}
   248```
   249
   250### 3.8 Angle Calculation (General)
   251
   252**Standard Formula:**
   253```javascript
   254function angle(p1, vertex, p2) {
   255  const v1 = { x: p1.x - vertex.x, y: p1.y - vertex.y };
   256  const v2 = { x: p2.x - vertex.x, y: p2.y - vertex.y };
   257
   258  const dot = v1.x * v2.x + v1.y * v2.y;
   259  const cross = v1.x * v2.y - v1.y * v2.x;
   260
   261  return Math.atan2(cross, dot) * (180 / Math.PI);
   262}
   263```
   264
   265---
   266
   267## 4. API Response Data Fields
   268
   269### 4.1 Side Landmarks Response
   270
   271| Field | Type | Description |
   272|-------|------|-------------|
   273| `success` | boolean | API call success status |
   274| `data.rotationAngle` | number | Head rotation in radians |
   275| `data.direction` | string | Profile direction ("left"/"right") |
   276| `data.center` | {x, y} | Face center coordinates |
   277| `data.crop` | object | Crop parameters for processing |
   278| `data.landmarks` | array | Array of 106 {x, y} coordinates |

# FaceIQ Labs - Facial Analysis Calculation Analysis Report

**Analysis Date:** 2025-12-18
**HAR File:** /Users/imorgado/Desktop/FACEIQ.har (68.13 MB)
**JavaScript Files:** /Users/imorgado/Desktop/FACEIQHAR/

---

## Executive Summary

This report documents the findings from reverse-engineering the FaceIQ Labs facial analysis platform. The analysis reveals that:

1. **Landmark detection is performed server-side** via API calls
2. **Side profile analysis uses 106 facial landmarks**
3. **Calculation formulas are NOT present in client-side JavaScript** - all computations happen on the backend
4. **The frontend is a Next.js React application** with minified production code

---

## 1. API Endpoints Discovered

### 1.1 Core Endpoints

| Endpoint | Method | Purpose |
|----------|--------|---------|
| `/api/auth/session` | GET | User session management |
| `/api/auth/callback/google` | GET | Google OAuth callback |
| `/api/faces` | GET/POST | Face image management |
| `/api/side-landmarks` | POST | **Side profile landmark detection** |
| `/api/subscription` | GET | User subscription status |
| `/api/analysis/unlock` | POST | Premium feature unlock |
| `/api/faces/[id]/surgery-consent` | POST | Surgery simulation consent |

### 1.2 Endpoint Details

#### /api/side-landmarks (POST)
**This is the key endpoint for landmark detection.**

**Request:** Image data posted to server
**Response Structure:**
```json
{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "rotationAngle": -0.4113050062109639,
    "direction": "right",
    "center": {"x": 381.039, "y": 479.534},
    "crop": {
      "x": 154,
      "y": 228,
      "width": 505,
      "height": 505,
      "scale": 2.029268292682927
    },
    "landmarks": [/* 106 coordinate pairs */],
    "bbox": [317, 316, 495, 644]
  }
}
```

#### /api/subscription (GET)

  "subscription": null,

```

---

## 2. Side Profile Landmark Data (106 Points)

The `/api/side-landmarks` endpoint returns 106 facial landmark coordinates for side profile analysis.

### 2.1 Landmark Coordinate Format
```json
{
  "x": 484.7926025390625,
  "y": 623.1043701171875
}
```

All coordinates are floating-point values representing pixel positions in the processed image.

### 2.2 Landmark Index Mapping (Inferred from Analysis)

Based on standard cephalometric analysis and the landmark count (106), the indices likely correspond to:

#### Face Contour (Indices 0-16)
| Index | Probable Feature |
|-------|-----------------|
| 0 | Menton (chin bottom) |
| 1-8 | Mandible contour |
| 9-16 | Cheek/Ear contour |

#### Nose Profile (Indices 17-33)
| Index | Probable Feature |
|-------|-----------------|
| 17 | Trichion (hairline reference) |
| 18-24 | Forehead/Nasion area |
| 25-33 | Nose bridge and tip |

#### Eye Region (Indices 34-51)
| Index | Probable Feature |
|-------|-----------------|
| 34-42 | Eye contour points |
| 43-51 | Brow and eyelid markers |

#### Nose/Lip Region (Indices 52-75)
| Index | Probable Feature |
|-------|-----------------|
| 52-63 | Nasal landmarks |
| 64-75 | Upper/lower lip markers |

#### Additional Points (Indices 76-105)
| Index | Probable Feature |
|-------|-----------------|
| 76-85 | Brow profile points |
| 86-95 | Ear and jaw markers |
| 96-105 | Precision adjustment points |

### 2.3 Key Anatomical Landmarks Referenced

From the landmark image URLs found in HAR:
- `hairline.webp` - Trichion
- `leftEyePupil.webp` / `rightEyePupil.webp` - Pupil centers
- `noseLeft.webp` / `noseRight.webp` - Alar base
- `lowerLip.webp` - Vermilion border
- `chinBottom.webp` - Menton
- `leftOuterEar.webp` / `rightOuterEar.webp` - Tragion
- `leftTemple.webp` / `rightTemple.webp` - Temporal points
- `leftEyeMedialCanthus.webp` - Inner eye corner
- `leftEyeLateralCanthus.webp` - Outer eye corner
- `leftEyeUpperEyelid.webp` / `leftEyeLowerEyelid.webp` - Eyelid margins
- `leftBrowHead.webp` / `leftBrowArch.webp` / `leftBrowTail.webp` - Brow points
- `leftUpperEyelidCrease.webp` - Crease position

---

## 3. Calculation Formulas (Server-Side)

**IMPORTANT:** The actual calculation formulas are NOT present in the client-side JavaScript. All calculations are performed server-side. The following are **standard formulas** used in facial analysis that the system likely implements:

### 3.1 FWHR (Facial Width-to-Height Ratio)

**Standard Formula:**
```
FWHR = Bizygomatic Width / Upper Face Height
     = (Zygion_L to Zygion_R) / (Nasion to Upper Lip)
```

**Typical Values:**
- Male ideal: 1.8 - 2.1
- Female ideal: 1.6 - 1.9

### 3.2 Golden Ratio Measurements

**Standard Formula:**
```
Phi (Golden Ratio) = 1.618

Measurements tested:
- Face length / Face width
- Lip to chin / Nose to lip
- Nose width / Mouth width
- Eye width / Interpupillary distance
```

### 3.3 Facial Thirds

**Standard Formula:**
```
Upper Third = Trichion to Glabella
Middle Third = Glabella to Subnasale
Lower Third = Subnasale to Menton

Ideal: Each third = 33.3% of total face height
```

### 3.4 Canthal Tilt

**Standard Formula:**
```
Canthal Tilt = atan2(
  (Lateral_Canthus_Y - Medial_Canthus_Y),
  (Lateral_Canthus_X - Medial_Canthus_X)
) * (180 / PI)

Positive value = positive canthal tilt (desirable)
Ideal range: +4 to +8 degrees
```

### 3.5 Nasolabial Angle (Side Profile)

**Standard Formula:**
```
Nasolabial Angle = angle between:
  - Line from Columella to Subnasale
  - Line from Subnasale to Labrale Superius

Ideal range: 90-120 degrees (varies by gender)
- Male: 90-95 degrees
- Female: 100-110 degrees
```

### 3.6 Gonial Angle (Side Profile)

**Standard Formula:**
```
Gonial Angle = angle at the Gonion point between:
  - Mandibular plane (Gonion to Menton)
  - Ramus line (Gonion to Condylion)

Ideal range: 120-130 degrees
```

### 3.7 Distance Calculation (General)

**Standard Formula:**
```javascript
function distance(p1, p2) {
  return Math.sqrt(
    Math.pow(p2.x - p1.x, 2) +
    Math.pow(p2.y - p1.y, 2)
  );
}
```

### 3.8 Angle Calculation (General)

**Standard Formula:**
```javascript
function angle(p1, vertex, p2) {
  const v1 = { x: p1.x - vertex.x, y: p1.y - vertex.y };
  const v2 = { x: p2.x - vertex.x, y: p2.y - vertex.y };

  const dot = v1.x * v2.x + v1.y * v2.y;
  const cross = v1.x * v2.y - v1.y * v2.x;

  return Math.atan2(cross, dot) * (180 / Math.PI);
}
```

Not exactly. Here's the honest breakdown:

## What We Have 

1. **106 Side Profile Landmark Coordinates** - The exact {x, y} positions FaceIQ detects
2. **Landmark Names** - hairline, chinBottom, eyeMedialCanthus, browArch, etc.
3. **Standard Industry Formulas** - FWHR, Golden Ratio, Canthal Tilt, Nasolabial Angle, Gonial Angle
4. **API Response Structure** - How data flows through the system

## What We Don't Have 

1. **FaceIQ's Exact Formulas** - All calculations happen server-side, not in the JavaScript
2. **Landmark Index Mapping** - We have 106 points but don't know which index = which facial feature
3. **Scoring/Weighting Logic** - How they convert measurements to scores
4. **"Harmony Analysis"** - Premium feature, completely hidden

## Can You Recreate It?

**Yes, but with standard formulas** - not FaceIQ's proprietary ones.

The standard formulas in the report (from academic cephalometric analysis) will give you **similar** results. For example:

```
FWHR = Bizygomatic Width / Upper Face Height
Canthal Tilt = atan2(lateral_y - medial_y, lateral_x - medial_x) * (180/)
```

These are industry-standard and should produce comparable measurements.

content.text: Yes, that would help capture the actual API responses with calculation results. Here's how to set up both options:

input.content:
# HTTPS Proxy Interception Setup Guide

This guide covers setting up Charles Proxy or mitmproxy to intercept HTTPS traffic and capture FaceIQ API responses.

---

## Option 1: mitmproxy (Free, Command-Line)

### Step 1: Install mitmproxy

```bash
# Using Homebrew
brew install mitmproxy

# Or using pip
pip3 install mitmproxy
```

### Step 2: Start mitmproxy

```bash
# Interactive terminal UI
mitmproxy

# Or web interface (recommended)
mitmweb

# Or dump to file
mitmdump -w faceiq_traffic.flow
```

Default proxy runs on `localhost:8080`

### Step 3: Install SSL Certificate (macOS)

```bash
# 1. Start mitmproxy first (it generates certs on first run)
mitmproxy

# 2. The certificate is at:
# ~/.mitmproxy/mitmproxy-ca-cert.pem

# 3. Install to macOS Keychain
sudo security add-trusted-cert -d -r trustRoot -k /Library/Keychains/System.keychain ~/.mitmproxy/mitmproxy-ca-cert.pem
```

**Or manually:**
1. Open Keychain Access
2. File  Import Items
3. Select `~/.mitmproxy/mitmproxy-ca-cert.pem`
4. Find "mitmproxy" in Keychain
5. Double-click  Trust  "Always Trust"

### Step 4: Configure Browser Proxy

**Chrome:**
```bash
# Launch Chrome with proxy
/Applications/Google\ Chrome.app/Contents/MacOS/Google\ Chrome --proxy-server="localhost:8080"
```

**Or system-wide (macOS):**
1. System Settings  Network  Wi-Fi  Details
2. Proxies  Web Proxy (HTTP)  `localhost:8080`
3. Proxies  Secure Web Proxy (HTTPS)  `localhost:8080`

### Step 5: Capture FaceIQ Traffic

```bash
# Filter only FaceIQ API calls
mitmproxy --set flow_detail=3 -w faceiq.flow

# Or with filtering
mitmdump -w faceiq.flow "~d faceiqlabs.com"
```

### Step 6: Export Captured Data

```bash
# Convert to HAR
mitmdump -nr faceiq.flow -w faceiq.har --set hardump=faceiq.har

# Or use Python script (see below)
```

---

## Option 2: Charles Proxy (GUI, Paid but 30-day trial)

### Step 1: Download & Install

1. Download from: https://www.charlesproxy.com/download/
2. Install the .dmg
3. Launch Charles

### Step 2: Install SSL Certificate (macOS)

1. In Charles: **Help  SSL Proxying  Install Charles Root Certificate**
2. Keychain Access opens automatically
3. Find "Charles Proxy CA" certificate
4. Double-click  Trust  "Always Trust"
5. Enter password to confirm

## Capturing FaceIQ Calculations

### What to Capture

1. **Login** - `/api/auth/session`
2. **Upload front face** - Watch for MediaPipe processing
3. **Upload side profile** - `/api/side-landmarks`
4. **View results** - **THIS IS THE KEY** - `/api/analysis/*` endpoints
5. **Premium features** - `/api/analysis/unlock` (if you have subscription)

### Key Endpoints to Watch

```
POST /api/side-landmarks      106 landmark coordinates
GET  /api/subscription        Quota info
POST /api/analysis/unlock     Premium calculations (need subscription)
GET  /api/faces               Face data
```

### Filtering in mitmproxy

```bash
# Only show FaceIQ API calls
mitmdump "~d faceiqlabs.com & ~u /api/"

# Show request and response bodies
mitmproxy --set flow_detail=3

# Save only API responses
mitmdump -w api_only.flow "~d faceiqlabs.com & ~u /api/ & ~s"
```

---

## Python Script to Parse mitmproxy Flows

Save this to extract API responses:

```python
#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Extract FaceIQ API responses from mitmproxy flow file"""

from mitmproxy import io as mitmio
from mitmproxy.exceptions import FlowReadException
import json
import os

FLOW_FILE = "faceiq.flow"
OUTPUT_DIR = "captured_api"

os.makedirs(OUTPUT_DIR, exist_ok=True)

with open(FLOW_FILE, "rb") as f:
    reader = mitmio.FlowReader(f)

    for i, flow in enumerate(reader.stream()):
        try:
            if "faceiqlabs.com/api" in flow.request.pretty_url:
                url = flow.request.pretty_url
                method = flow.request.method

                # Get endpoint name
                endpoint = url.split("faceiqlabs.com")[1].split("?")[0]
                safe_name = endpoint.replace("/", "_").strip("_")

                print(f"[{i}] {method} {endpoint}")

                # Get response
                if flow.response:
                    content_type = flow.response.headers.get("content-type", "")

                    if "json" in content_type:
                        try:
                            body = json.loads(flow.response.content)

                            # Save to file
                            filename = f"{i:03d}_{method}_{safe_name}.json"
                            with open(os.path.join(OUTPUT_DIR, filename), "w") as out:
                                json.dump({
                                    "url": url,
                                    "method": method,
                                    "status": flow.response.status_code,
                                    "response": body
                                }, out, indent=2)

                            print(f"   Saved: {filename}")

                            # Check for calculation data
                            if "score" in str(body).lower():
                                print(f"   CONTAINS SCORE DATA!")
                            if "ratio" in str(body).lower():
                                print(f"   CONTAINS RATIO DATA!")
                            if "calculation" in str(body).lower():
                                print(f"   CONTAINS CALCULATION DATA!")

                        except json.JSONDecodeError:
                            print(f"   Non-JSON response")

        except FlowReadException as e:
            print(f"Error reading flow: {e}")

print(f"\nAll responses saved to: {OUTPUT_DIR}/")
```

---

## Troubleshooting

### Certificate Not Trusted

```bash
# Check if cert is installed
security find-certificate -c "mitmproxy" /Library/Keychains/System.keychain

# Remove and reinstall
sudo security delete-certificate -c "mitmproxy" /Library/Keychains/System.keychain
sudo security add-trusted-cert -d -r trustRoot -k /Library/Keychains/System.keychain ~/.mitmproxy/mitmproxy-ca-cert.pem
```

### Chrome Ignoring Proxy

```bash
# Kill all Chrome processes first
pkill -9 "Google Chrome"

# Then launch with proxy flag
/Applications/Google\ Chrome.app/Contents/MacOS/Google\ Chrome --proxy-server="localhost:8080"
```

### macOS Ventura+ Security

You may need to:
1. System Settings  Privacy & Security
2. Allow the proxy app (Charles/mitmproxy)
3. May need to disable SIP for some operations (not recommended)

### HSTS / Certificate Pinning

Some sites use certificate pinning. FaceIQ likely doesn't, but if you see SSL errors:
- Try Firefox (more lenient)
- Use `--ignore-certificate-errors` flag for Chrome (risky!)

---

## Quick Start Commands

```bash
# Install
brew install mitmproxy

# Start web UI
mitmweb

# Install cert (after starting mitmproxy once)
sudo security add-trusted-cert -d -r trustRoot -k /Library/Keychains/System.keychain ~/.mitmproxy/mitmproxy-ca-cert.pem

# Set system proxy (or use browser extension)
networksetup -setwebproxy Wi-Fi localhost 8080
networksetup -setsecurewebproxy Wi-Fi localhost 8080

# Capture traffic
# Now visit https://beta.faceiqlabs.com in your browser

# When done, disable proxy
networksetup -setwebproxystate Wi-Fi off
networksetup -setsecurewebproxystate Wi-Fi off
```

---

## Security Warning

 **While proxy is active:**
- All HTTPS traffic is decrypted through your proxy
- Don't do banking/sensitive activities
- Disable proxy when done
- Remove the CA certificate when finished with research

---
